{{short description|French actor}} {{Use dmy dates|date=March 2016}} [[File:Luciano Emmer, Marina Vlady, Magali Noël en Bernard Fresson (1960).jpg|thumb|330px|[[Luciano Emmer]], [[Marina Vlady]], [[Magali Noël]] and Bernard Fresson (1 June 1960)]] '''Bernard Fresson''' (27 May 1931 &ndash; 20 October 2002) was a [[French people|French]] [[actor]] who primarily worked in film.
Born in [[Reims]], [[France]], to a French baker, Fresson attended the [[Lycée privé Sainte-Geneviève]], majoring in law.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bernard Fresson - Cinémathèque française |url=http://cinema.encyclopedie.personnalites.bifi.fr/index.php?pk=45739 |website=cinema.encyclopedie.personnalites.bifi.fr |language=French}}</ref> He studied in Tania Balachova's drama class in [[Paris]] and later became part of [[Jean Vilar]]'s [[Théâtre National Populaire]] at the [[Palais de Chaillot]].<ref name="Guardian">{{cite news |last1=Bergan |first1=Ronald |title=Obituary: Bernard Fresson |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2002/dec/05/guardianobituaries |work=The Guardian |date=December 5, 2002}}</ref>
He made his on-screen debut in the [[Alain Renais]] film ''[[Hiroshima mon amour]]'' as a German soldier. His notable film roles include: Gilbert in ''[[La Prisonnière (film)|La Prisonnière]]'' (1968), Inspector Barthelmy in [[John Frankenheimer]]'s ''[[French Connection II]]'' (1974), Scope in [[Roman Polanski]]'s ''[[The Tenant]]'' (1976), Francis in ''[[Garçon!]]'' (1983), Morin in ''[[Street of No Return]]'' (1989) and Vincent Malivert in ''[[Place Vendôme (film)|Place Vendôme]]'' (1998). He also appeared in the 1969 [[Costa-Gavras]] film ''[[Z (1969 film)|Z]]''.
For his roles in ''Garçon!'' and ''Place Vendôme'', Fresson received a [[César Award|César]] nomination for Best Supporting Actor.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bernard Fresson - Académie des César |url=http://www.academie-cinema.org/en/ceremony/palmares-par-recherche/,personne,6009.html |website=www.academie-cinema.org |accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref>
